    detailedExplanationExpert: `This is a clean example of the Prosecutor's Fallacy in its purest form: directly substituting P(E|¬G) for P(¬G|E). Bayes' theorem requires the prior P(¬G) and the total P(E). The prosecutor's figure of 1/50,000 only measures the fingerprint's discriminating power in isolation, not the posterior probability of innocence. The error is logically identical to confusing P(smoke|fire) with P(fire|smoke).`,
