    concept: "Probability & Evidence",
    difficulty: 1,
    subLevel: SubLevel.BEGINNER,
    question: `A politician says, "Crime is down 10% this year!" but omits that violent crime specifically rose 15%. What fallacy is this?`,
    options: ["Cherry-picking", "Base-rate Neglect", "Gambler’s Fallacy", "Survivorship Bias"],
    correct_option_index: 0,
    explanation: `The politician selectively highlighted only the favorable statistic while ignoring the unfavorable one.`,
    detailedExplanationBeginner: `Cherry-picking means choosing only the evidence that makes your case look good. Here, the politician picked one crime stat that dropped while hiding the violent crime stat that rose.`,
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: `This is a classic example of cherry-picking in political rhetoric. Aggregate crime statistics can mask divergent trends within subcategories. By presenting only the aggregate decline, the speaker avoids engaging with the more policy-relevant subset.`,
    detailedExplanationExpert: `This rhetorical maneuver exploits the ecological fallacy and Simpson’s paradox. By presenting only the aggregate decline, the speaker avoids engaging with the more policy-relevant subset—violent crime. This selective disclosure is a textbook instance of cherry-picking (suppressed evidence).`,
