    explanation: `The student only surveyed those who survived (passed) the exam, missing everyone who used the guide and still failed.`,
    detailedExplanationBeginner: `It's like asking only people who got job offers if the job fair was useful. The people who didn't get jobs aren't in your sample! The student should also talk to people who used the guide but still failed.`,
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: `By interviewing only passing students, the researcher creates a survivorship-filtered sample. Students who used the study guide but failed the exam are invisible. Without the denominator—total guide users—the numerator—passing guide users—is meaningless.`,
    detailedExplanationExpert: `This scenario demonstrates how survivorship bias corrupts outcome evaluation. The student calculates P(pass | used guide and passed) which is trivially 1.0, rather than P(pass | used guide), which is the quantity of interest. The correct experimental design would be a randomized controlled trial: randomly assign students to use or not use the guide, then compare pass rates.`,
    questionFormat: "standard"
