    detailedExplanationIntermediate: `The study conditions on survival (10+ years) and then identifies correlates (diversity). This creates a survivorship bias because failed companies—some of which had diverse leadership—are excluded. The observed correlation between diversity and performance may be spurious if failed companies also had diverse leadership at similar rates.`,
    detailedExplanationExpert: `This is a corporate-survivorship confound in organizational research. The study commits what econometricians call "conditioning on a post-treatment variable": survival is partially determined by performance, which is the dependent variable. Conditioning on survival introduces selection bias because the factors that predict survival are correlated with the factors being studied. The correct methodology requires: (1) a cohort study tracking all companies from founding, (2) measuring diversity and performance longitudinally, (3) using survival analysis to model the relationship between diversity and failure risk. Research using complete cohorts shows that the diversity-performance relationship is more nuanced than survivorship-filtered studies suggest.`,
