    concept: "Probability & Evidence",
    difficulty: 3,
    subLevel: SubLevel.EXPERT,
    question: `A company's HR department reports that employee satisfaction increased after implementing a new policy, based on surveys of employees who responded. However, the most dissatisfied employees had already quit. What fallacy is this?`,
    options: ["Survivorship Bias", "Hasty Generalization", "Anecdotal Evidence", "Base-rate Neglect"],
    correct_option_index: 0,
    explanation: `The survey misses the most dissatisfied employees who left—employee turnover before the survey creates a survivorship-filtered sample that makes the policy appear effective.`,
    detailedExplanationBeginner: `It's like asking "do you like our school?" to only the students who stayed, after all the unhappy ones transferred away! Of course the remaining students are happier—they're the ones who wanted to stay!`,
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: `The survey has two survivorship filters: (1) only current employees are surveyed (quitters are excluded), (2) only employees who chose to respond are counted. The pre-survey turnover removed the most dissatisfied employees, creating a floor effect in satisfaction scores. The "improvement" may reflect turnover of dissatisfied employees rather than genuine policy impact.`,
    detailedExplanationExpert: `This is an employee-turnover survivorship bias in organizational research. The mechanism: (1) a policy change occurs, (2) the most dissatisfied employees quit before the survey, (3) the post-policy survey captures only survivors, (4) satisfaction appears to improve. The correct analysis requires: (1) tracking all employees from before the policy change, (2) comparing satisfaction among continuous employees (not just survivors), (3) modeling the relationship between policy, satisfaction, and turnover using survival analysis, (4) accounting for differential attrition. Research shows that turnover-based satisfaction improvements are typically 2-3x larger than genuine policy effects.`,
    questionFormat: "standard"
