    detailedExplanationIntermediate: `The study identifies correlates of successful maintenance in the survivor population. However, these same habits may be common among people who tried to maintain but failed—the study cannot observe this. The "common habits" might be necessary but not sufficient, or might be coincidental to success driven by genetics, socioeconomic factors, or other unmeasured variables.`,
    detailedExplanationExpert: `This is a behavior-change survivorship bias in health research. The study conditions on successful maintenance (5+ years of weight loss) and identifies correlates, but cannot establish causation because: (1) people who tried the same habits but failed are invisible, (2) maintenance success may be driven by unmeasured factors (genetics, metabolism, social support), (3) the habits might be consequences of maintenance rather than causes. The correct methodology requires: (1) a full cohort study tracking all weight-loss attempters, (2) survival analysis modeling predictors of maintenance vs. regain, (3) randomized controlled trials of specific interventions. The National Weight Control Registry (which this scenario describes) is valuable but subject to exactly this survivorship bias.`,
    questionFormat: "standard"
