    detailedExplanationIntermediate: `The study conditions on survival to old age in the Mediterranean population and compares against a different population. This creates a double survivorship bias: (1) only Mediterranean survivors are studied, (2) early deaths (possibly from poor diet or other factors) are excluded. The observed "protective effect" may partly reflect the exclusion of non-survivors.`,
    detailedExplanationExpert: `This is a population-level survivorship bias in nutritional epidemiology. The study conditions on survival and then infers dietary causation. The correct methodology requires: (1) prospective cohort studies from mid-life tracking diet and disease outcomes, (2) Mediterranean and non-Mediterranean populations matched on baseline characteristics, (3) intention-to-treat analysis (tracking all participants regardless of diet adherence), (4) controlling for confounders (socioeconomic status, physical activity, genetics). The well-known PREDIMED trial provides stronger causal evidence through randomized design, though it also suffered from methodological issues.`,
