    detailedExplanationBeginner: `It's like a poker player saying "I always win!" because they only count their current chips and forget the money they lost in hands they folded! The REIT threw away its losers and only counts its winners.`,
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: `The REIT's reported returns suffer from portfolio survivorship bias: properties that underperformed were sold (often at a loss) and removed from the performance calculation. The "average annual return" only reflects currently-held properties, not the full investment history. The correct calculation would include realized losses from sold properties.`,
    detailedExplanationExpert: `This is a financial-instrument survivorship bias that affects investment performance reporting. The mechanism: (1) REIT acquires properties, (2) underperforming properties are sold at a loss, (3) losses are removed from the portfolio return calculation, (4) remaining properties show high average returns. The correct methodology requires: (1) time-weighted returns including realized losses, (2) money-weighted returns (IRR) for the full portfolio lifecycle, (3) comparison against relevant benchmarks, (4) disclosure of portfolio turnover and realized gains/losses. SEC regulations require REITs to report total returns including realized gains/losses, but marketing materials often use the survivorship-filtered metric.`,
