    detailedExplanationIntermediate: `The study conditions on high ratings and identifies correlates, but these correlates may not distinguish great teachers from average ones—they might simply be common to all teachers. The missing population (low-rated teachers) could share the same "engaging style" but lack other qualities. The correct analysis would compare high-rated against low-rated teachers.`,
    detailedExplanationExpert: `This is an education-quality survivorship bias. The study conditions on the outcome (5-star rating) and identifies correlates, but cannot establish what distinguishes great teachers from poor ones because the full distribution of teacher quality is not observed. The "engaging teaching style" finding might be common across all teachers, with the difference being class size, subject difficulty, or grading leniency. The correct methodology requires: (1) measuring teaching quality across all teachers, (2) comparing high-rated against low-rated teachers on multiple dimensions, (3) controlling for student characteristics and course difficulty, (4) using multi-level models to account for nested data structures.`,
