    correct_option_index: 0,
    explanation: `You ignored the base rate of crime (0.5%). Even though most burglars are male, the vast majority of men are not burglars.`,
    detailedExplanationBeginner: `The base rate is that only 0.5% of people commit burglary. 80% of that tiny 0.5% are men, but that means only 0.4% of all people are male burglars. The 99.6% of men who aren't burglars is the base rate you ignored.`,
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: `This confuses P(male|burglar) with P(burglar|male). The statistic says 80% of burglars are male, not 80% of males are burglars. The base rate of crime (0.5%) means the overwhelming majority of men never commit burglary.`,
    detailedExplanationExpert: `This is the 'confusion of the inverse' characteristic of base-rate neglect. P(burglar|male) = P(male|burglar) × P(burglar) / P(male) ≈ 0.8 × 0.005 / 0.5 ≈ 0.008 or 0.8%. The base rate of crime makes the actual probability tiny. This error frequently appears in profiling contexts.`,
