    id: 7102,
    level: 7,
    persona_stage: PersonaStage.DOLPHIN,
    concept: "Protocole Social",
    difficulty: 3,
    subLevel: SubLevel.EXPERT,
    question: `A museum's artifact authentication process correctly identifies fakes 99.5% of the time. The base rate of forgeries in the collection is 0.1%. An artifact is authenticated as genuine. A curator says `,
    options: ["Base-rate Neglect", "Gambler's Fallacy", "Prosecutor's Fallacy", "Cherry-picking"],
    correct_option_index: 0,
    explanation: `The actual probability is about 99.95%. In this case, the very low forgery base rate (0.1%) combined with high accuracy (99.5%) means the authentication is quite reliable—but 'definitely' still ignores the remaining uncertainty.`,
    detailedExplanationBeginner: `The base rate is 0.1% forgery. With 0.5% false positive rate on 99.9% genuine items, the false positive count is very small. P(genuine|authenticated genuine) ≈ 99.95%.`,
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: `In 100,000 artifacts: 100 are fake (0.5 miss, so 99.5% sensitivity catches ~99.5) and 99,900 are genuine (0.5% falsely called fake = 499.5). Wait—the system says 'genuine,' so: 99,900 × 0.995 = 99,400.5 correctly called genuine, plus 100 × 0.005 = 0.5 fakes called genuine. Total 'genuine': 99,401. Actual genuine: 99,400.5/99,401 ≈ 99.999%. The 'definitely' is actually well-justified here, but strictly speaking 'definitely' ignores the residual uncertainty.`,
    detailedExplanationExpert: `P(genuine|authenticated) = (0.995 × 0.999) / [(0.995 × 0.999) + (0.005 × 0.001)] ≈ 99.9995%. In this case, the authentication is extremely reliable. However, the 'definitely' still technically commits a mild base-rate neglect by ignoring the residual 0.0005% chance. This is an edge case where base-rate neglect has minimal practical impact.`,
    questionFormat: "standard"
